Note:
High-level thread-coordination API — the public phase/rendezvous objects for
the Runa runtime concurrency system.

This is the runtime-facing coordination layer. It does NOT touch OS futexes or
the cross-platform synchronization facade directly. Instead it COMPOSES the
already-completed runtime mutex (mutex.runa) and runtime condition variable
(condition_variable.runa) object layers into three classic coordination
primitives, each of which couples a counter (or a flag) with the
mutex+condvar pair so threads can rendezvous on a shared milestone:

  - WAITGROUP (Go-style): a monotonic work counter. Producers register pending
    work with waitgroup_add, each unit of work calls waitgroup_done as it
    completes, and one or more coordinators block in waitgroup_wait until the
    counter drains to zero. Used to join a dynamic fan-out of tasks without
    knowing their thread identities.
  - COUNTDOWNLATCH: a single-use gate initialized with a fixed count. Each
    arriving party calls latch_count_down once; threads in latch_wait are
    released together when the count reaches zero. Used for one-shot "wait until
    N things have happened" barriers (startup readiness, phase completion).
  - ONCE: an idempotent initializer. once_do runs a supplied function pointer
    exactly one time across every caller and every thread; all later calls
    observe that it already ran and return without re-invoking. Used for lazy
    one-time setup (singletons, global tables) that must not race.

COMPOSITION CONTRACT: every wait re-checks its predicate inside a While loop
around condvar_wait, so a spurious wakeup (a wake delivered without the
predicate actually being satisfied) simply re-blocks rather than escaping the
loop. The RuntimeMutex handle returned by mutex_new IS the object handed to
condvar_wait — condvar_wait extracts the underlying sync_core handle from the
mutex's offset 0 itself, so this layer stores and passes the mutex handle
directly and never reaches below the object API.

WaitGroup layout (24 bytes):
    offset 0:   mutex     — RuntimeMutex handle guarding the counter
    offset 8:   condvar   — RuntimeCondVar handle signalled when the counter drains
    offset 16:  counter   — outstanding work units

CountDownLatch layout (24 bytes):
    offset 0:   mutex     — RuntimeMutex handle guarding the count
    offset 8:   condvar   — RuntimeCondVar handle signalled when the count hits zero
    offset 16:  count     — parties still to arrive

Once layout (16 bytes):
    offset 0:   mutex     — RuntimeMutex handle guarding the done flag and the run
    offset 8:   done      — 0 not yet run, 1 already run
:End Note

Import "runtime/concurrency/synchronization/mutex.runa" as Mutex
Import "runtime/concurrency/synchronization/condition_variable.runa" as CondVar
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/assembly/call_indirect.runa" as Call

Note: WaitGroup object layout
Constant WG_SIZE as Integer is 24
Constant WG_OFF_MUTEX as Integer is 0
Constant WG_OFF_CONDVAR as Integer is 8
Constant WG_OFF_COUNTER as Integer is 16

Note: Status codes returned by the WaitGroup API
Constant WG_OK as Integer is 0
Constant WG_ERR_NULL as Integer is 0 minus 1

Note: CountDownLatch object layout
Constant LATCH_SIZE as Integer is 24
Constant LATCH_OFF_MUTEX as Integer is 0
Constant LATCH_OFF_CONDVAR as Integer is 8
Constant LATCH_OFF_COUNT as Integer is 16

Note: Status codes returned by the CountDownLatch API
Constant LATCH_OK as Integer is 0
Constant LATCH_ERR_NULL as Integer is 0 minus 1

Note: Once object layout
Constant ONCE_SIZE as Integer is 16
Constant ONCE_OFF_MUTEX as Integer is 0
Constant ONCE_OFF_DONE as Integer is 8

Note: Status codes returned by the Once API
Constant ONCE_OK as Integer is 0
Constant ONCE_ERR_NULL as Integer is 0 minus 1

Note: ============================================================================
Note: WaitGroup — Go-style dynamic work-counter join
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "waitgroup_new" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Create a WaitGroup object. The synchronization mechanism comes entirely from
    a composed RuntimeMutex (guarding the counter) and a RuntimeCondVar (waking
    coordinators when the counter drains); this layer adds the counter and a
    stable object identity callers hold.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Allocate the 24-byte WaitGroup, create the underlying runtime mutex and
    condvar, store both handles, and initialize the counter to 0. On any
    allocation/creation failure, release whatever was acquired in reverse order
    and return 0 so no half-built object escapes.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One small allocation plus one mutex_new and one condvar_new (each of which
    allocates its own control block and an OS primitive). Cold path: done once
    per WaitGroup.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Failure returns 0 (NULL); callers MUST check before use. No partially
    initialized object is ever returned.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let wg be proc allocate from Memory with WG_SIZE
    If wg is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let m be proc mutex_new from Mutex
    If m is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with wg
        Return 0
    End If

    Let cv be proc condvar_new from CondVar
    If cv is equal to 0:
        proc mutex_destroy from Mutex with m
        proc deallocate from Memory with wg
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with wg, WG_OFF_MUTEX, m
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with wg, WG_OFF_CONDVAR, cv
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with wg, WG_OFF_COUNTER, 0
    Return wg
End Process

Process called "waitgroup_add" takes wg as Integer, delta as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Register additional (or, with a negative delta, retire) outstanding work
    before launching it. Adjusting the counter must be atomic with respect to
    waitgroup_done and waitgroup_wait, so it happens under the WaitGroup mutex.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Acquire the mutex, load the counter, add delta, store it back. If the new
    value is at or below zero, the group is already satisfied, so broadcast the
    condvar to release any coordinators currently waiting before releasing the
    mutex. Return WG_OK.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One mutex_acquire / mutex_release pair plus two field accesses; a single
    condvar_broadcast only on the transition that drains the counter.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null object returns WG_ERR_NULL without touching memory. The counter is only
    ever read or written while the mutex is held, so concurrent adds and dones
    cannot interleave a torn update.
    @End Security_Scope

    If wg is equal to 0:
        Return WG_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let m be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with wg, WG_OFF_MUTEX
    Let cv be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with wg, WG_OFF_CONDVAR
    proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with m

    Let counter be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with wg, WG_OFF_COUNTER
    Let new_counter be counter plus delta
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with wg, WG_OFF_COUNTER, new_counter
    If new_counter is less than or equal to 0:
        proc condvar_broadcast from CondVar with cv
    End If

    proc mutex_release from Mutex with m
    Return WG_OK
End Process

Process called "waitgroup_done" takes wg as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Signal that one unit of registered work has completed. When the last unit
    finishes the counter reaches zero and every coordinator blocked in
    waitgroup_wait must be released.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Acquire the mutex, decrement the counter by one, store it back, and when it
    reaches (or has already fallen to) zero broadcast the condvar so all waiters
    re-evaluate their predicate. Release the mutex and return WG_OK.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One mutex_acquire / mutex_release pair plus two field accesses; a single
    condvar_broadcast only on the draining transition.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null object returns WG_ERR_NULL. The decrement and the zero test are
    performed under the mutex so the broadcast is published atomically with the
    counter reaching zero.
    @End Security_Scope

    If wg is equal to 0:
        Return WG_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let m be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with wg, WG_OFF_MUTEX
    Let cv be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with wg, WG_OFF_CONDVAR
    proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with m

    Let counter be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with wg, WG_OFF_COUNTER
    Let new_counter be counter minus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with wg, WG_OFF_COUNTER, new_counter
    If new_counter is less than or equal to 0:
        proc condvar_broadcast from CondVar with cv
    End If

    proc mutex_release from Mutex with m
    Return WG_OK
End Process

Process called "waitgroup_wait" takes wg as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Block the calling coordinator until all registered work has completed, i.e.
    until the counter drains to zero. Multiple coordinators may wait at once and
    are all released together when the group is satisfied.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Acquire the mutex, then loop: while the counter is still greater than zero,
    condvar_wait on the WaitGroup's condvar paired with its mutex. The mutex
    handle stored at offset 0 is passed directly to condvar_wait, which extracts
    the underlying sync_core handle itself. The While loop re-checks the counter
    after every wake, so a spurious wakeup simply re-blocks instead of returning
    early. Once the counter is zero, release the mutex and return WG_OK.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One mutex_acquire / mutex_release pair. The thread parks in condvar_wait
    with no busy-waiting and is woken only by the draining broadcast; the loop
    re-acquires the mutex once per wake to re-test the predicate.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null object returns WG_ERR_NULL without touching the wait queue. The counter
    predicate is only ever evaluated while the mutex is held, and condvar_wait
    re-acquires that same mutex before returning, so the held/predicate contract
    is preserved across every iteration.
    @End Security_Scope

    If wg is equal to 0:
        Return WG_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let m be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with wg, WG_OFF_MUTEX
    Let cv be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with wg, WG_OFF_CONDVAR
    proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with m

    Let counter be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with wg, WG_OFF_COUNTER
    While counter is greater than 0:
        proc condvar_wait from CondVar with cv, m
        Set counter to proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with wg, WG_OFF_COUNTER
    End While

    proc mutex_release from Mutex with m
    Return WG_OK
End Process

Process called "waitgroup_destroy" takes wg as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Release the composed mutex and condvar and free the WaitGroup object. Must
    not be called while any coordinator is still waiting on the group.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Read both composed handles, delegate to condvar_destroy and mutex_destroy
    (each of which frees its facade control block and OS primitive), then
    deallocate the WaitGroup object.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One condvar_destroy, one mutex_destroy, and one deallocate. Cold path.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null object returns WG_ERR_NULL. Destroying a WaitGroup with active waiters
    is a logic error.
    @End Security_Scope

    If wg is equal to 0:
        Return WG_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let m be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with wg, WG_OFF_MUTEX
    Let cv be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with wg, WG_OFF_CONDVAR
    proc condvar_destroy from CondVar with cv
    proc mutex_destroy from Mutex with m
    proc deallocate from Memory with wg
    Return WG_OK
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CountDownLatch — single-use "wait until N events" gate
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "latch_new" takes count as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Create a CountDownLatch initialized to a fixed number of expected events.
    The mechanism is a composed RuntimeMutex (guarding the count) and
    RuntimeCondVar (waking waiters when the count reaches zero); this layer adds
    the count and a stable object identity.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Allocate the 24-byte latch, create the underlying mutex and condvar, store
    both handles, and initialize the count to the requested value. On any
    allocation/creation failure, release whatever was acquired in reverse order
    and return 0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One small allocation plus one mutex_new and one condvar_new. Cold path: done
    once per latch.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Failure returns 0 (NULL); callers MUST check before use. A latch created with
    a count of zero is already open: latch_wait returns immediately.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let l be proc allocate from Memory with LATCH_SIZE
    If l is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let m be proc mutex_new from Mutex
    If m is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with l
        Return 0
    End If

    Let cv be proc condvar_new from CondVar
    If cv is equal to 0:
        proc mutex_destroy from Mutex with m
        proc deallocate from Memory with l
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with l, LATCH_OFF_MUTEX, m
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with l, LATCH_OFF_CONDVAR, cv
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with l, LATCH_OFF_COUNT, count
    Return l
End Process

Process called "latch_count_down" takes l as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Record the arrival of one expected event. When the final event arrives the
    count reaches zero and the gate opens, releasing every waiter together. The
    count never drops below zero, so extra count-downs after the gate has opened
    are harmless no-ops.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Acquire the mutex, load the count, and only when it is still greater than
    zero decrement it and store it back; once it reaches zero broadcast the
    condvar to release all waiters. Decrementing below zero is suppressed so a
    late arrival cannot re-close an already-open gate. Release the mutex and
    return LATCH_OK.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One mutex_acquire / mutex_release pair plus field accesses; a single
    condvar_broadcast only on the transition that opens the gate.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null object returns LATCH_ERR_NULL. The count test, decrement, and broadcast
    are all performed under the mutex so the gate opens atomically with the count
    reaching zero.
    @End Security_Scope

    If l is equal to 0:
        Return LATCH_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let m be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with l, LATCH_OFF_MUTEX
    Let cv be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with l, LATCH_OFF_CONDVAR
    proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with m

    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with l, LATCH_OFF_COUNT
    If count is greater than 0:
        Let new_count be count minus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with l, LATCH_OFF_COUNT, new_count
        If new_count is equal to 0:
            proc condvar_broadcast from CondVar with cv
        End If
    End If

    proc mutex_release from Mutex with m
    Return LATCH_OK
End Process

Process called "latch_wait" takes l as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Block the caller until the latch has counted all the way down to zero. Any
    number of threads may wait; they are all released together when the gate
    opens. A latch already at zero releases the caller immediately.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Acquire the mutex, then loop: while the count is still greater than zero,
    condvar_wait on the latch's condvar paired with its mutex (the mutex handle
    is passed directly; condvar_wait extracts the sync_core handle itself). The
    While loop re-reads the count after every wake, so a spurious wakeup simply
    re-blocks. Once the count is zero, release the mutex and return LATCH_OK.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One mutex_acquire / mutex_release pair. The thread parks in condvar_wait
    with no busy-waiting and is woken only by the gate-opening broadcast.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null object returns LATCH_ERR_NULL without touching the wait queue. The count
    predicate is only evaluated while the mutex is held, and condvar_wait
    re-acquires that same mutex before returning.
    @End Security_Scope

    If l is equal to 0:
        Return LATCH_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let m be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with l, LATCH_OFF_MUTEX
    Let cv be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with l, LATCH_OFF_CONDVAR
    proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with m

    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with l, LATCH_OFF_COUNT
    While count is greater than 0:
        proc condvar_wait from CondVar with cv, m
        Set count to proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with l, LATCH_OFF_COUNT
    End While

    proc mutex_release from Mutex with m
    Return LATCH_OK
End Process

Process called "latch_get_count" takes l as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Report how many events remain before the gate opens. Used for diagnostics
    and progress reporting; callers must not build control flow on the value
    because it can change the instant the call returns.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Acquire the mutex, read the count into a local, release the mutex, and return
    the captured value so the read is never torn against a concurrent
    count-down.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One mutex_acquire / mutex_release pair plus one field load.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null object returns 0. Advisory only; the count may change immediately after
    the call returns.
    @End Security_Scope

    If l is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let m be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with l, LATCH_OFF_MUTEX
    proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with m
    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with l, LATCH_OFF_COUNT
    proc mutex_release from Mutex with m
    Return count
End Process

Process called "latch_destroy" takes l as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Release the composed mutex and condvar and free the latch object. Must not be
    called while any thread is still waiting on the latch.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Read both composed handles, delegate to condvar_destroy and mutex_destroy,
    then deallocate the latch object.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One condvar_destroy, one mutex_destroy, and one deallocate. Cold path.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null object returns LATCH_ERR_NULL. Destroying a latch with active waiters is
    a logic error.
    @End Security_Scope

    If l is equal to 0:
        Return LATCH_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let m be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with l, LATCH_OFF_MUTEX
    Let cv be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with l, LATCH_OFF_CONDVAR
    proc condvar_destroy from CondVar with cv
    proc mutex_destroy from Mutex with m
    proc deallocate from Memory with l
    Return LATCH_OK
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Once — run a function pointer exactly one time across all threads
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "once_new" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Create a Once object. The mechanism is a single composed RuntimeMutex that
    serializes the first-run race; this layer adds a done flag and a stable
    object identity. No condvar is needed because once_do never blocks waiting
    for another party — it only needs mutual exclusion around the flag test and
    the single invocation.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Allocate the 16-byte Once, create the underlying mutex, store its handle, and
    initialize the done flag to 0 (not yet run). On any allocation/creation
    failure, release whatever was acquired and return 0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One small allocation plus one mutex_new. Cold path: done once per Once.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Failure returns 0 (NULL); callers MUST check before use.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let o be proc allocate from Memory with ONCE_SIZE
    If o is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let m be proc mutex_new from Mutex
    If m is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with o
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with o, ONCE_OFF_MUTEX, m
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with o, ONCE_OFF_DONE, 0
    Return o
End Process

Process called "once_do" takes o as Integer, fn as Integer, arg as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Run the supplied initializer function pointer exactly once, no matter how
    many callers or threads invoke once_do. The first caller to win the mutex
    observes the cleared done flag, runs fn, and sets the flag; every later
    caller observes the set flag under the same mutex and skips the call. This is
    the idempotent-initialization guarantee used for lazy singletons and global
    setup.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Acquire the mutex. If the done flag is still 0, invoke the function pointer
    via call_indirect_1 with the caller's argument, then set the done flag to 1
    so no subsequent caller re-runs it. The flag test and the invocation happen
    under the same lock, so concurrent first callers cannot both enter the body.
    Release the mutex and return ONCE_OK.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One mutex_acquire / mutex_release pair. The wrapped function runs only on the
    very first call; every later call is just a flag load plus the lock
    round-trip with no indirect call.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null object returns ONCE_ERR_NULL without touching memory or invoking fn. The
    initializer runs while the Once mutex is held, so an initializer that itself
    calls once_do on the SAME Once would deadlock — callers must not re-enter the
    same Once from within its own initializer.
    @End Security_Scope

    If o is equal to 0:
        Return ONCE_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let m be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with o, ONCE_OFF_MUTEX
    proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with m

    Let done be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with o, ONCE_OFF_DONE
    If done is equal to 0:
        proc call_indirect_1 from Call with fn, arg
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with o, ONCE_OFF_DONE, 1
    End If

    proc mutex_release from Mutex with m
    Return ONCE_OK
End Process

Process called "once_has_run" takes o as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Report whether the one-time initializer has already executed. Callers that
    can take a fast path once setup is complete use this to avoid the once_do
    lock round-trip.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Acquire the mutex, read the done flag into a local, release the mutex, and
    return the captured value so the read cannot race the first runner's flag
    store.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One mutex_acquire / mutex_release pair plus one field load.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null object returns 0. The returned value is a stable snapshot: once it is 1
    it can never revert, so a true result is permanently authoritative.
    @End Security_Scope

    If o is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let m be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with o, ONCE_OFF_MUTEX
    proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with m
    Let done be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with o, ONCE_OFF_DONE
    proc mutex_release from Mutex with m
    Return done
End Process

Process called "once_destroy" takes o as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Release the composed mutex and free the Once object. Must not be called while
    another thread may still invoke once_do on it.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Read the mutex handle, delegate to mutex_destroy, then deallocate the Once
    object.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One mutex_destroy plus one deallocate. Cold path.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null object returns ONCE_ERR_NULL. Destroying a Once that another thread may
    still call is a logic error.
    @End Security_Scope

    If o is equal to 0:
        Return ONCE_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let m be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with o, ONCE_OFF_MUTEX
    proc mutex_destroy from Mutex with m
    proc deallocate from Memory with o
    Return ONCE_OK
End Process
